The XRD patterns of the obtained materials are shown in Fig. 2A, which shows that all samples consist of a mixture of three phases: anatase, rutile, and brookite. The prominent peaks at 2θ values of 25.34°, 37.93°, 48.10°, 54.02°, 55.13°, 62.77°, 68.94°, 70.35°, 75.32°, and 82.89° correspond to the crystal plane of TiO2 anatase with parameters (101), (004), (200), (105), (211), (204), (116), (220), (215) (
                           JCPDs No.01-073-1764
                        ). As shown in Table 1
                        , the dominant component of the three-phase mixture was determined to be anatase. However, in the NTC sample, the presence of diffraction peaks at angles 30.8°, 42.6°, and 46.0° suggests that the synthesized Ni-doped TiO2 possesses orthorhombic crystal brookite phase, as indicated by the (211), (221), and (302) lattice planes (
                           JCPDs No.01-072-0100
                        ). It means that the addition of Ni increases the amount of the brookite phase in the obtained material. Conversely, the diffraction peaks associated with the rutile TiO2 phase were either weakened or absent at certain angles, precisely 27.5°, 36.0°, and 56.6° which are attributed to the (110), (101), and (220) lattice planes of the tetragonal crystalline rutile phase (
                           JCPDs No.01-079-6029
                        ). This observation suggests that the doping process altered the crystal structure, resulting in the transformation from rutile to brookite phases. The average nanoparticle size was calculated using the Scherrer eq. (SI. Eq. 1) and is presented in Table 1. Notably, no crystalline peaks of Nickel (Ni) species (i.e. Nickel oxide, Nickel hydroxide, or Nickel oxyhydroxide) could be observed in the X-ray diffraction (XRD) analysis. The reason could be due to the complete doping of Nickel ions into the TiO2 structure that resulted in a small red shift in the peak relating to the (101) plane of the TiO2 anatase in the NTC sample (Fig. 2A, inset) [31,32]. Table 1 also shows the phase ratio of the pure TiO2 and NTC samples that were estimated following the literature [33]. The results suggest that the difference in the atomic radius of Ni2+ (0.072 nm) and Ti4+ (0.068 nm) [34] leads to lattice defects within the anatase or rutile structures. As a result, the TiO bonds were broken, allowing the rearrangement of the [TiO6] octahedra and, consequently, the phase transformation from anatase and/or rutile forms to brookite [35]. It also causes a change in the nanoparticle size. However, the low content of Ni dopant in the sample may be another reason for the absence of XRD patterns of Ni compounds [36].

X-ray Photoelectron Spectroscopy (XPS) is employed to study the chemical bonding states of surface elements in the modified nanomaterials (Fig. 3
                        ). The survey spectrum reveals information about elements such as Ti, C, and O (Fig. 3A). The C 1s peak at 284.80 eV is utilized to calibrate other elements. The Ti 2p spectrum shown in Fig. 3B displays two distinct peaks at 458.6 and 464.4 eV, which are identified as typical peaks of Ti4+ [49], and Ti3+ at 463.6 and 458.0 eV [50]. The appearance of the Ti3+ signal is attributed to the charge imbalance caused by the substitution of Ni2+ for Ti4+ [48,50], despite the absence of Ti2O3 signals in the XRD analysis results. Ni was introduced into the TiO2 structure at an insignificant concentration (0.05 %wt), Zhang et al. [51] demonstrated that only at sufficiently high concentrations, Ni0 (Nickel molecule) could exist on TiO2. The presence of Ni2+ within the TiO2 crystal lattice leads to charge imbalance, which can readily facilitate the formation of Oxygen vacancies (Ov) in the form of Ti4+-Ov-Ni2+. This process induces charge imbalance throughout the crystalline lattice, prompting some Ti4+ atoms to be reduced to Ti3+ resulting in the formation of Ni2+-TiO2-Ov [52,53]. Consequently, a mixture of Ti3+ and Ti4+ states is formed within the sample (as shown in Fig. 3B). The high-resolution C 1s spectrum reveals three peaks with corresponding binding energies of 284.8 eV, 286.39 eV, and 288.60 eV, which are attributed to adventitious carbon: CC, CO, and CO, respectively (Fig. 3C) [54]. Additionally, with the presence of CQDs in the sample and in conjunction with the enhanced C 1s signal, these observations can confirm the presence of CQDs with a significant number of functional groups such as COH, COOH, or CO [55]. The presence of the carbon layer on the surface of Ni-doped TiO2 directly affects the signal intensity of Ni in XPS analysis. The presence of the carbon layer leads to a decrease in the intensity of Ni 2p due to the coverage of carbon [56], which will be discussed below. Fig. 3D illustrates the XPS spectrum of O 1s, where the peak is further analyzed into three smaller components. The small peak at 529.75 eV is characteristics of O species in the Ti4+
                        O bond [57]; In the meantime, the peak at 530.96 eV can be assigned to O atoms binding to doped Ni atoms. The formation of bonds between doped Ni atoms and O atoms within the TiO2 lattice leads to the shift the BE of these O atoms to a higher level [53]. This point can be used as an assumption to explain the presence of this peak, along with the implication for the Ni appearance in the NTC lattice. The peak at 532.00 eV corresponds to O atoms in double CO bonds or surface hydroxyl groups (

                              OH
                              −

                        ) [58]. Notably, the results depicted in Fig. 3A reveal that no Ni signal is detected in the NTC sample; in other words, the Ni signal is highly obscured and unable to provide accurate results. One reason for this could be the coating of CQDs on the surface by carbon quantum dots, as mentioned earlier. Furthermore, the insignificant concentration of Ni (<0.05 % wt.) makes it difficult to detect the presence of Ni on the surface of TiO2. However, we detected a valence band edge of NTC at around 1.79 eV (Fig. 3E), while the valence band edge of pure TiO2 should be at 2.73 eV [59]. This result implies the incorporation of Ni atoms in the TiO2 structure so that the hybridization of Ni 3d states with O 2p may cause the valence band shift [59,60].

The evidence for the presence of doped Ni atoms in the NTC sample was indicated by the ICP-MS analysis. The results are listed in Table 2
                        , including the degradation efficiency (follow SI. Eq. 2) and the COD measurements (follow SI. Eq. 3) of the mixture after 150 min of CIP degradation using the materials as photocatalysts. The ICP-MS analysis confirmed the presence of Ni in the NTC catalyst sample, with a content of 0.049 % by weight, which is very similar to the theoretical value. Further analysis of the elements and their distribution on the surface of NTC material was carried out using the EDX mapping method (Fig. 4
                        ). The results show that only three main elements can be observed, including carbon (C), titanium (Ti), and oxygen (O). The amount of C indicates the presence of CQDs on the surface of the catalyst sample. The distribution of the elements is relatively even, promising the formation of an effective heterogeneous catalytic system [61]. However, there was no signal of Ni element on the EDX mapping spectrum, possibly due to its content being too low to be detected or because the Ni atoms were not on the material's surface but located deeply within the crystal structure [58,62].
